    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "10558615_988c239f",
        "filename": "src/images/SkJpegEncoder.h",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 56,
      "author": {
        "id": 5185
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-05-01T14:58:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e It seems weird to me that this will only return false due to a dumb client. (i.e. client passed a bad value or keeps calling after\n\u003e the encode is complete)\n\nAgreed.\n\n\u003e Maybe there\u0027s no need to return a boolean? What will the call site look like? It kind of looks like someone might call something\n\u003e like\n\n\u003e  while (encodeRows(\u003csome value\u003e)\n\n\u003e But then they don\u0027t need to use a loop, since they can just pass the height (or some really large number).\n\nI can make this void.  I was on the fence anyway...  FWIW, I think the callsite will be something like.\n\nfor (int i \u003d 0; i \u003c remainingRows; i++) {\n  encodeRows(1);\n\n  if (out of time) {\n    break;\n  }\n}\n\n\u003e If the client passes \u003c\u003d 0, maybe that should be a signal to encode all lines remaining?\n\nI\u0027m not sure I like this, but I can see how it makes returning void more reasonable.  I\u0027d rather just assert and do nothing.",
      "parentUuid": "c871919e_1dcb6e6f",
